<HEAD>Chronology of Events In Nicaragua Since Sandinista Victory in 1979</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following is a chronology of events in
Nicaragua since the left-wing Sandinistas came to power in 1979
after leading the civil war that ousted President Anastasio Somoza:
   July 17, 1979 _ Somoza, whose family had ruled Nicaragua with
U.S. support since the 1930s, flees to Miami.
   July 19, 1979 _ Victorious Sandinista guerrillas enter Managua
and begin their rule.
   November 1980 _ First attacks launched by anti-Sandinista rebels
known as Contras _ the name coming from a contraction of the Spanish
word for counter-revolutionaries.
   February 1981 _ Reagan administration announces suspension of aid
to Nicaragua and accuses Nicaragua of supporting leftist guerrillas
in El Salvador.
   July 8, 1981 _ Eden Pastora, known as Commander Zero, defects
from the Sandinista government and becomes a leader of Nicaragua
rebels.
   November 1982 _ Reports emerge alleging covert U.S. aid to the
Contras.
   May 1, 1983 _ Nicaragua claims violations of its territory by
U.S. spy planes and warships.
   April 6-7, 1984 _ Commando units operating from a U.S. ship plant
mines in Nicaragua's ports.
   April 9, 1984 _ Nicaragua asks the International Court of Justice
to order the United States to cease aiding the Contras. The Reagan
administration had announced it would not accept the court's
jurisdiction.
   Jan. 10, 1985 _ Daniel Ortega is inaugurated as president
following national elections.
   March 20, 1985 _ The U.S. House of Representatives defeats
President Ronald Reagan's proposal for $100 million in military and
humanitarian aid to the Contras but later reverses itself and passes
the package on June 25.
   May 1, 1985 _ Reagan announces a trade embargo against Nicaragua.
   June 27, 1985 _ The International Court of Justice says U.S.
support for the Contras is a violation of the U.N. charter's ban on
use of force.
   Aug. 13, 1985 _ The U.S. Senate approves Reagan's $100 million
aid package.
   Oct. 5, 1986 _ An American-manned cargo plane is shot down in
southern Nicaragua. The surviving crew member, Eugene Hasenfus, is
captured and implicates the CIA in the Contra-supply operation.
Hasenfus subsequently is freed.
   Nov. 25, 1986 _ Attorney General Edwin Meese III discloses that
some of the profits from the sale of American arms to Iran had been
secretly diverted to the Contras in an operation run by Marine Lt.
Col. Oliver North.
   Aug. 7, 1987 _ Five Central American presidents sign a peace plan
sponsored by Costa Rican President Oscar Arias. It includes
amnesties for political prisoners, democratic reforms, an end to
foreign aid for rebel forces and a prohibition against one country
allowing guerrillas to use its territory to attack another.
   Jan. 19, 1988 _ Nicaragua lifts a 6-year-old state of emergency.
   Feb. 3, 1988 _ The U.S. Congress cuts off arms aid to the Contras
but continues non-military aid.
   Mar. 21, 1988 _ The Sandinistas and Contras meet face-to-face for
the first time in Nicaraguan territory.
   April 1, 1988 _ A formal truce begins.
   May 31, 1988 _ The Sandinistas extend truce on a monthly basis _
a practice they have continued. The Contras say they consider the
truce indefinite. Talks break off but fighting declines.
   July 11, 1988 _ U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton is expelled with
the government accusing him of inciting destabilization. Washington
expels Carlos Tunnerman, Nicaragua's envoy to the United States.
   Jan. 30, 1989 _ Ortega announces a harsh austerity program to
combat inflation that surpasses 20,000 percent annually.
   Feb. 14, 1989 _ Five Central American countries sign an accord at
a summit in El Salvador. Ortega promises early elections in exchange
for dismantling of the Contras, based in Honduran jungle camps.
   April 18, 1989 _ President Bush signs a $49 million measure that
continues non-lethal aid to the Contras.
</TEXT>
